836|"CHAPTER 1. THE EGG"|FALSE
836|"It began with the day when it was almost the Fifth of November, and a"|FALSE
836|"doubt arose in some breast--Robert's, I fancy--as to the quality of the"|FALSE
836|"fireworks laid in for the Guy Fawkes celebration."|FALSE
836|"'They were jolly cheap,' said whoever it was, and I think it was Robert,"|FALSE
836|"'and suppose they didn't go off on the night? Those Prosser kids would"|FALSE
836|"have something to snigger about then.'"|FALSE
836|"'The ones _I_ got are all right,' Jane said; 'I know they are, because"|FALSE
836|"the man at the shop said they were worth thribble the money--'"|FALSE
836|"'I'm sure thribble isn't grammar,' Anthea said."|FALSE
836|"'Of course it isn't,' said Cyril; 'one word can't be grammar all by"|FALSE
836|"itself, so you needn't be so jolly clever.'"|FALSE
836|"Anthea was rummaging in the corner-drawers of her mind for a very"|FALSE
836|"disagreeable answer, when she remembered what a wet day it was, and how"|FALSE
836|"the boys had been disappointed of that ride to London and back on the"|FALSE
836|"top of the tram, which their mother had promised them as a reward for"|FALSE
836|"not having once forgotten, for six whole days, to wipe their boots on"|FALSE
836|"the mat when they came home from school."|FALSE
836|"So Anthea only said, 'Don't be so jolly clever yourself, Squirrel. And"|FALSE
836|"the fireworks look all right, and you'll have the eightpence that your"|FALSE
836|"tram fares didn't cost to-day, to buy something more with. You ought to"|FALSE
836|"get a perfectly lovely Catharine wheel for eightpence.'"|FALSE
836|"'I daresay,' said Cyril, coldly; 'but it's not YOUR eightpence anyhow--'"|FALSE
836|"'But look here,' said Robert, 'really now, about the fireworks. We don't"|FALSE
836|"want to be disgraced before those kids next door. They think because"|FALSE
836|"they wear red plush on Sundays no one else is any good.'"|FALSE
836|"'I wouldn't wear plush if it was ever so--unless it was black to be"|FALSE
836|"beheaded in, if I was Mary Queen of Scots,' said Anthea, with scorn."|FALSE
836|"Robert stuck steadily to his point. One great point about Robert is the"|FALSE
836|"steadiness with which he can stick."|FALSE
836|"'I think we ought to test them,' he said."|FALSE
836|"'You young duffer,' said Cyril, 'fireworks are like postage-stamps. You"|FALSE
836|"can only use them once.'"|FALSE
836|"'What do you suppose it means by \"Carter's tested seeds\" in the"|FALSE
836|"advertisement?'"|FALSE
836|"There was a blank silence. Then Cyril touched his forehead with his"|FALSE
836|"finger and shook his head."|FALSE
836|"'A little wrong here,' he said. 'I was always afraid of that with poor"|FALSE
836|"Robert. All that cleverness, you know, and being top in algebra so"|FALSE
836|"often--it's bound to tell--'"|FALSE
836|"'Dry up,' said Robert, fiercely. 'Don't you see? You can't TEST seeds if"|FALSE
836|"you do them ALL. You just take a few here and there, and if those"|FALSE
836|"grow you can feel pretty sure the others will be--what do you call"|FALSE
836|"it?--Father told me--\"up to sample\". Don't you think we ought to sample"|FALSE
836|"the fire-works? Just shut our eyes and each draw one out, and then try"|FALSE
836|"them.'"|FALSE
836|"'But it's raining cats and dogs,' said Jane."|FALSE
836|"'And Queen Anne is dead,' rejoined Robert. No one was in a very good"|FALSE
836|"temper. 'We needn't go out to do them; we can just move back the table,"|FALSE
836|"and let them off on the old tea-tray we play toboggans with. I don't"|FALSE
836|"know what YOU think, but _I_ think it's time we did something, and"|FALSE
836|"that would be really useful; because then we shouldn't just HOPE the"|FALSE
836|"fireworks would make those Prossers sit up--we should KNOW.'"|FALSE
836|"'It WOULD be something to do,' Cyril owned with languid approval."|FALSE
836|"So the table was moved back. And then the hole in the carpet, that"|FALSE
836|"had been near the window till the carpet was turned round, showed most"|FALSE
836|"awfully. But Anthea stole out on tip-toe, and got the tray when cook"|FALSE
836|"wasn't looking, and brought it in and put it over the hole."|FALSE
836|"Then all the fireworks were put on the table, and each of the four"|FALSE
836|"children shut its eyes very tight and put out its hand and grasped"|FALSE
836|"something. Robert took a cracker, Cyril and Anthea had Roman candles;"|FALSE
836|"but Jane's fat paw closed on the gem of the whole collection, the"|FALSE
836|"Jack-in-the-box that had cost two shillings, and one at least of the"|FALSE
836|"party--I will not say which, because it was sorry afterwards--declared"|FALSE
836|"that Jane had done it on purpose. Nobody was pleased. For the worst of"|FALSE
836|"it was that these four children, with a very proper dislike of anything"|FALSE
836|"even faintly bordering on the sneakish, had a law, unalterable as those"|FALSE
836|"of the Medes and Persians, that one had to stand by the results of a"|FALSE
836|"toss-up, or a drawing of lots, or any other appeal to chance, however"|FALSE
836|"much one might happen to dislike the way things were turning out."|FALSE
836|"'I didn't mean to,' said Jane, near tears. 'I don't care, I'll draw"|FALSE
836|"another--'"|FALSE
836|"'You know jolly well you can't,' said Cyril, bitterly. 'It's settled."|FALSE
836|"It's Medium and Persian. You've done it, and you'll have to stand by"|FALSE
836|"it--and us too, worse luck. Never mind. YOU'LL have your pocket-money"|FALSE
