836|"certain it will manage somehow.'"|FALSE
836|"Mother's bell rang again."|FALSE
836|"'Oh, Eliza's never answered it,' cried Anthea; 'she never does. Oh, I"|FALSE
836|"must go.'"|FALSE
836|"And she went."|FALSE
836|"Her heart beat bumpingly as she climbed the stairs. Mother would be"|FALSE
836|"certain to notice her eyes--well, her hand would account for that. But"|FALSE
836|"the Lamb--"|FALSE
836|"'No, I must NOT think of the Lamb, she said to herself, and bit her"|FALSE
836|"tongue till her eyes watered again, so as to give herself something"|FALSE
836|"else to think of. Her arms and legs and back, and even her tear-reddened"|FALSE
836|"face, felt stiff with her resolution not to let mother be worried if she"|FALSE
836|"could help it."|FALSE
836|"She opened the door softly."|FALSE
836|"'Yes, mother?' she said."|FALSE
836|"'Dearest,' said mother, 'the Lamb--'"|FALSE
836|"Anthea tried to be brave. She tried to say that the Lamb and Robert were"|FALSE
836|"out. Perhaps she tried too hard. Anyway, when she opened her mouth no"|FALSE
836|"words came. So she stood with it open. It seemed easier to keep from"|FALSE
836|"crying with one's mouth in that unusual position."|FALSE
836|"'The Lamb,' mother went on; 'he was very good at first, but he's pulled"|FALSE
836|"the toilet-cover off the dressing-table with all the brushes and"|FALSE
836|"pots and things, and now he's so quiet I'm sure he's in some dreadful"|FALSE
836|"mischief. And I can't see him from here, and if I'd got out of bed to"|FALSE
836|"see I'm sure I should have fainted.'"|FALSE
836|"'Do you mean he's HERE?' said Anthea."|FALSE
836|"'Of course he's here,' said mother, a little impatiently. 'Where did you"|FALSE
836|"think he was?'"|FALSE
836|"Anthea went round the foot of the big mahogany bed. There was a pause."|FALSE
836|"'He's not here NOW,' she said."|FALSE
836|"That he had been there was plain, from the toilet-cover on the floor,"|FALSE
836|"the scattered pots and bottles, the wandering brushes and combs, all"|FALSE
836|"involved in the tangle of ribbons and laces which an open drawer had"|FALSE
836|"yielded to the baby's inquisitive fingers."|FALSE
836|"'He must have crept out, then,' said mother; 'do keep him with you,"|FALSE
836|"there's a darling. If I don't get some sleep I shall be a wreck when"|FALSE
836|"father comes home.'"|FALSE
836|"Anthea closed the door softly. Then she tore downstairs and burst into"|FALSE
836|"the nursery, crying--"|FALSE
836|"'He must have wished he was with mother. He's been there all the time."|FALSE
836|"\"Aggety dag--\"'"|FALSE
836|"The unusual word was frozen on her lip, as people say in books."|FALSE
836|"For there, on the floor, lay the carpet, and on the carpet, surrounded"|FALSE
836|"by his brothers and by Jane, sat the Lamb. He had covered his face and"|FALSE
836|"clothes with vaseline and violet powder, but he was easily recognizable"|FALSE
836|"in spite of this disguise."|FALSE
836|"'You are right,' said the Phoenix, who was also present; 'it is evident"|FALSE
836|"that, as you say, \"Aggety dag\" is Bosh for \"I want to be where my mother"|FALSE
836|"is,\" and so the faithful carpet understood it.'"|FALSE
836|"'But how,' said Anthea, catching up the Lamb and hugging him--'how did"|FALSE
836|"he get back here?'"|FALSE
836|"'Oh,' said the Phoenix, 'I flew to the Psammead and wished that your"|FALSE
836|"infant brother were restored to your midst, and immediately it was so.'"|FALSE
836|"'Oh, I am glad, I am glad!' cried Anthea, still hugging the baby. 'Oh,"|FALSE
