836|"something quite different next time. Now, my Lamb, Panther'll clean you"|FALSE
836|"a little. Come on.'"|FALSE
836|"'I hope the beetles won't go wishing,' said Cyril, as they rolled up the"|FALSE
836|"carpet."|FALSE
836|"Two days later mother was well enough to go out, and that evening the"|FALSE
836|"coconut matting came home. The children had talked and talked, and"|FALSE
836|"thought and thought, but they had not found any polite way of telling"|FALSE
836|"the Phoenix that they did not want it to stay any longer."|FALSE
836|"The days had been days spent by the children in embarrassment, and by"|FALSE
836|"the Phoenix in sleep."|FALSE
836|"And, now the matting was laid down, the Phoenix awoke and fluttered down"|FALSE
836|"on to it."|FALSE
836|"It shook its crested head."|FALSE
836|"'I like not this carpet,' it said; 'it is harsh and unyielding, and it"|FALSE
836|"hurts my golden feet.'"|FALSE
836|"'We've jolly well got to get used to its hurting OUR golden feet,' said"|FALSE
836|"Cyril."|FALSE
836|"'This, then,' said the bird, 'supersedes the Wishing Carpet.'"|FALSE
836|"'Yes,' said Robert, 'if you mean that it's instead of it.'"|FALSE
836|"'And the magic web?' inquired the Phoenix, with sudden eagerness."|FALSE
836|"'It's the rag-and-bottle man's day to-morrow,' said Anthea, in a low"|FALSE
836|"voice; 'he will take it away.'"|FALSE
836|"The Phoenix fluttered up to its favourite perch on the chair-back."|FALSE
836|"'Hear me!' it cried, 'oh youthful children of men, and restrain your"|FALSE
