836|"lead-pencils. They're cheaper if you buy them by the packet.'"|FALSE
836|"This was a thing that they had always wanted to do, but it needed the"|FALSE
836|"great excitement of a funeral pyre and a parting from a beloved Phoenix"|FALSE
836|"to screw them up to the extravagance."|FALSE
836|"The people at the stationer's said that the pencils were real"|FALSE
836|"cedar-wood, so I hope they were, for stationers should always speak"|FALSE
836|"the truth. At any rate they cost one-and-fourpence. Also they spent"|FALSE
836|"sevenpence three-farthings on a little sandal-wood box inlaid with"|FALSE
836|"ivory."|FALSE
836|"'Because,' said Anthea, 'I know sandalwood smells sweet, and when it's"|FALSE
836|"burned it smells very sweet indeed.'"|FALSE
836|"'Ivory doesn't smell at all,' said Robert, 'but I expect when you burn"|FALSE
836|"it it smells most awful vile, like bones.'"|FALSE
836|"At the grocer's they bought all the spices they could remember the names"|FALSE
836|"of--shell-like mace, cloves like blunt nails, peppercorns, the long"|FALSE
836|"and the round kind; ginger, the dry sort, of course; and the beautiful"|FALSE
836|"bloom-covered shells of fragrant cinnamon. Allspice too, and caraway"|FALSE
836|"seeds (caraway seeds that smelt most deadly when the time came for"|FALSE
836|"burning them)."|FALSE
836|"Camphor and oil of lavender were bought at the chemist's, and also a"|FALSE
836|"little scent sachet labelled 'Violettes de Parme'."|FALSE
836|"They took the things home and found Cyril still on guard. When they had"|FALSE
836|"knocked and the golden voice of the Phoenix had said 'Come in,' they"|FALSE
836|"went in."|FALSE
836|"There lay the carpet--or what was left of it--and on it lay an egg,"|FALSE
